Japan, South Korea, Malaysia, Philippines: Asia Bonds and Currency Preview

-- B y   V .   R a m a k r i s h n a n
-- 
2011-05-08T22:09:13Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-08/japan-south-korea-malaysia-philippines-asia-bonds-and-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in  Asia ’s bonds and currencies
today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the previous
trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan : Chief Cabinet Secretary Yukio Edano will hold media
briefings at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. in  Tokyo .  The  Bank of Japan  will release at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo
minutes of its April 6-7 board meeting.  Hiromasa Yonekura, chairman of Japan’s largest business
lobby, or Keidanren, will have a press briefing at 3:30 p.m. in
Tokyo.  The yield on the 1.3 percent government bond due March 2021
was 1.140 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 80.64 per dollar at 7:03 a.m. in Tokyo.  South Korea : The central bank will sell a combined 2.2
trillion won ($2 billion) of 91-day and one-year notes. The
government will sell 2 trillion won of five-year bonds.  The yield on South Korea’s 5 percent bond due June 2020 was
4.44 percent. The won was at 1,083.34 per dollar.  Taiwan: The  trade surplus  was $1.84 billion in April,
compared with $1.77 billion in March, according to a Bloomberg
News survey of economists before the data is published today.  The yield on the 1.375 percent bond due March 2021 was 1.39
percent, according to Gretai Securities Market. The Taiwan
dollar was at NT$28.778.  Malaysia: The central bank will sell a combined 2 billion
ringgit ($666 million) of 86- and 308-day bills. It will also
sell 1 billion ringgit of 121-day Islamic notes.  The yield on the benchmark 4.16 percent note due July 2021
was at 4.04 percent. The ringgit was at 3.0025.  Philippines : The central bank will report M3 money-supply
data for March today. Supply grew 9.8 percent from a year
earlier in February.  The yield on the 6.50 percent bond due April 2021 was 6.40
percent, according to Tradition Financial Services. The peso was
at 43.08.  To contact the reporter on this story:
